# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-jacks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The **2021 Kellogg's strike** was a labor strike started on October 5, 2021, and ended December 21, 2021, involving about 1,400 workers for food manufacturer Kellogg's, unionized as members of the Bakery, Confectionery, Tobacco Workers and Grain Millers' International Union (BCTGM).
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The strike affected all of Kellogg's cereal-producing plants in the United States, consisting of plants in Battle Creek, Michigan; Omaha, Nebraska; Lancaster, Pennsylvania; and Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] It is one of several strikes conducted by the BCTGM in 2021, including strike action against Frito-Lay and Nabisco.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The strike is the first to affect Kellogg's Battle Creek plant since 1972, and the first at the Lancaster plant since 1985.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The strike ended after union workers voted to approve a new five-year labor contract.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Kellogg's is an American food manufacturer that derives about a third of its profits from its line of breakfast cereals, which includes brands such as Froot Loops and Frosted Flakes.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] In the United States, the company operated four cereal-producing plants in Battle Creek, Michigan (also where the company is headquartered); Omaha, Nebraska; Lancaster, Pennsylvania; and Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Going into October 2021, the company had been negotiating for over a year with the Bakery, Confectionery, Tobacco Workers and Grain Millers' International Union (BCTGM), a labor union that represents about 1,400 workers at these plants.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] One worker, describing the situation at the Lancaster plant, compared it to a "death of a thousand cuts".
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] While the contract between the union and company had expired in 2020, an extension renewed the existing contract until October 2021.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] On September 8 and 9, 2021, both sides submitted their proposals for a new contract and entered into discussions on them.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] However, during the negotiations, the parties could not agree on several key issues, including policies regarding health care, holidays, retirement benefits, and vacation time.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] In particular, Kellogg's was seeking to expand a two-tier employee system composed of "legacy" and "transitional" employees.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] According to the company, legacy employees average $35 per hour, and newer "transitional" employees make $22 per hour.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Under the system that had been in place in the prior five-year contract, transitional employees received less pay and reduced benefits compared to the legacy employees, but only 30% of all employees could be classified as transitional.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Kellogg's, however, was seeking to remove this cap, which the union alleged would cause a majority of employees to become classified as transitional.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The union was opposed to these changes and also stated that the company was threatening to move some production work to Mexico if these changes were not implemented.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The strike began at 1:00 a.m. the next day, October 5, 2021, with picketing commencing outside Kellogg's facilities.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The strike affected all four of Kellogg's American production facilities, with all of them ceasing operations.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The same day, the company stated that they were "implementing contingency plans" to reduce supply disruptions, with one union member stating that the company would try to bring in strikebreakers.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The company later clarified that they would be using "salaried employees and third-party resources" to cover for the strikers.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Additionally, *Newsweek* reported that whether the strike would significantly affect supply of Kellogg's products remained unclear.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Shortly after the start of the strike, Battle Creek Mayor Mark Behnke urged both sides to return to negotiations.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] On October 11, third-party contractors began to arrive at Kellogg's plants to serve as replacements for the striking workers.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The next day, Kellogg's issued a press release in which they clarified the "myths" and "facts" of the contract proposal and working conditions at their plants.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Following this, the president of Omaha's Local 50G stated that he was recommending strikers return to work for a 90-day period under the terms of the previous contract while a new contract could be ratified.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Despite this, a negotiator for Local 50G stated on October 13 that negotiations remained at an impasse.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] That same day, a large rally was held near the factory that was attended by strike supporters and members of several other labor union groups, including members of the AFL–CIO's Omaha Federation of Labor.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The rally's speaker was the president emeritus of that federation, who had previously worked at the Kellogg's plant.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Around this same time, a photograph of a striker picketing through a torrential rainstorm in Omaha on October 12 went viral online, with many sharing the image and commenting in support of the strike.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] On October 14, several members of the Nebraska Legislature, including Carol Blood, Megan Hunt, Mike McDonnell, and Tony Vargas, issued a press release in support of the strikers and urging Kellogg's to bargain in good faith with the union.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The agreement would also give all transitional employees a promotion to legacy if they had worked for the company for 4 years, and would have included enhanced dental and vision benefits for all workers.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Transitional employees would also gain additional vacation time based on their tenure with the company.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] However, the contract would have also preserved the two-tiered wage system favored by company management, the removal of which was the primary objective of the union.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The union membership overwhelmingly rejected the tentative agreement in a December 5 vote.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Following the vote, on December 7, Kellogg's management announced they would seek to replace all 1,400 striking workers.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] On December 21, about 1,400 Kellogg workers approved a collective bargaining agreement, ending the strike, which had lasted 77 days.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] After various calls on social media, made after the announcement that workers would be fired, a boycott was initiated.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] The subreddit r/antiwork, devoted to discussions on worker exploitation by the rich and powerful, began a campaign in solidarity with striking workers to flood Kellogg's job application site when Kellogg's opened up applications to replace striking workers.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] Reddit users also created automated scripts and defeated attempts by Kellogg's to block automated applications.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] When this made recruiting replacement workers difficult, Kellogg's switched to hiring through staffing agencies instead of direct recruitment.
[src:apple-jacks/2021-kellogg-s-strike] A spokesperson for Kellogg's denied claims that the website had crashed, and said that the hiring process was "fully operational".
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] The introduction of All-Bran in 1916 came on the heels of the success of Kellogg's Bran Flakes a year earlier.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] It was sold in a red and green box, similar to most Kellogg's cereals at the time.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] After finding great success in the U.S. market, Kellogg's began distribution in the United Kingdom and other markets in 1922.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] The current ingredients of All-Bran Original are wheat bran, sugar, corn and barley malt extract, salt, and the following added vitamins and minerals: iron, thiamine hydrochloride (vitamin B1), d-calcium pantothenate (vitamin B5), pyridoxine hydrochloride (vitamin B6), and folic acid.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] It contains 33% fiber, 78% of natural wheat bran's 43%.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] The second highest ingredient, after wheat bran, is sugar (18%).
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] All-Bran Buds is similar with added psyllium; its 39% fiber analysis is close to that of natural wheat bran.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] Despite the name, the principal ingredient in All-Bran Flakes is whole grain wheat, not bran.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] It contains only 15% fiber, equivalent to 34% wheat bran.
[src:apple-jacks/all-bran] All-Bran received five stars out of five on the Australian Government's health star ratings.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] Originally, the Apple Jacks were only orange and O-shaped, until 1998 when the green O-shapes were added to the cereals.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] In a marketing promotion in December 2003, the green pieces changed their shape to X's for a few months.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] More recently, Apple Jacks has introduced New Apple Jacks "Crashers" – a unique cereal piece that replicates a mid-2007 advertising campaign when mascots Apple and CinnaMon were accidentally fused together.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The latest (limited) edition, in 2010, are Apple Clones, with red pieces shaped like apples.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] In 2001, Apple Jacks was brought to Canada in a Limited Edition box.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] Apple Jacks were later released in Australia and can be found at Woolworths and Aldi, alongside Kellogg's Australia's Apple Jacks LCMs, a puffed rice snack bar with marshmallow flavour and Apple Jacks flavoured sprinkles.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The first Apple Jacks mascot in the 1960s was "Apple Jack", a figure made from cutting a mouth onto an apple and applying a hat and pieces of cereal for eyes.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] Television advertisements featuring Apple Jack had the tagline “A bowl a day keeps the bullies away!”, but was later altered to “A bowl a day gives you energy to play!”.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] In the late 1960s the box depicted an "Apple Car" with pieces of cereal for wheels.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] Around 1971, the official mascots became "The Apple Jacks Kids", a simplistically drawn animated boy and girl.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The commercials featured the children singing and tumbling around all day.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] Their reign lasted for 21 years, making them the most well-known Apple Jacks mascots and most universally associated with the cereal in the public's memory.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] During this time, the Apple Jacks jingle became an integral part of the ad campaign: "A is for apple, J is for Jacks, Cinnamon-toasty Apple Jacks!" This campaign was retired in 1992.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] Starting in 1992, there was an advertising campaign that featured children expressing their enjoyment of Apple Jacks, regardless of its lack of apple flavor.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The slogan for this campaign became "We eat what we like".
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The shift toward marketing cereals directly at children signaled the growing recognition of children's influence on family purchases.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The commercials took place in normal kid hang-outs, such as: at school, the garage, ballet class, and the kitchen, in the hall/hallway/door jamb, among others.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] In each commercial, a group of children are having Apple Jacks, when suddenly, some other people, such as adults or jealous kids, bash the group claiming it does not taste like apples and asks why they love it so much.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The group then explains their love of the cereal usually by just saying, "We just do", and at the end of the commercial, would pose for a group Polaroid.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] As of 2004, the marketing mascots were a carefree Jamaican cinnamon stick named CinnaMon and an accident-prone apple named Bad Apple.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] Labeled as *Apple Jacks Adventures* in print advertising, the commercials focused on CinnaMon upstaging Bad Apple by reaching a bowl of Apple Jacks before he can, in spite of the apple's attempts to stop him.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The campaign was slated to be retired in 2007, and replaced by a retread of the 1990s campaign focused on children, but fan response to Apple and CinnaMon helped them remain as the mascots.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] In 2007, Apple and CinnaMon were fused together with CinnaMon sticking through the center of Apple with both of their legs at the bottom of their body.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] They remained this way for a few of the commercials until they became unstuck by a special machine.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] According to the label on the box, in 2010, each 28 gram serving had 100 calories, three grams of dietary fiber, and 12 grams of sugar.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] In 2013, Kellogg's Apple Jacks introduced a new multi-grain cereal called "Cinnamon Jacks", with the cinnamon stick, CinnaMon, as its sole mascot.
[src:apple-jacks/apple-jacks] The cereal is flavored with brown sugar and cinnamon.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Kelly Flatley and Brendan Synnott are the co-founders of Bear Naked granola.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Flatley came up with the name – “bear” which evoked the outdoors, while “naked” implied the absence of additives.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] In college, Flatley made granola in her dorm room and shared it with friends.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Flatley met Synnott in 2002 in Darien, Connecticut.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Flatley was making her granola through the night and delivering it to local stores the next morning.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] They became business partners and began using a commercial kitchen.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] They were the only employees of the company at the time, so they created, distributed, and marketed the granola themselves.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Initially, commercial distributors would not sell them raw materials, so they bought bulk from their local Costco.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Synnott and Flatley pitched their products to organic and natural markets and increased the company's presence in stores.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] In 2003, Stew Leonard's supermarket chain in New York picked up their granola, which helped pull the company into commercial success.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] In 2007, Flatley and Synnott were approached by Kashi, a subsidiary of the Kellogg Company.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] The partners sold Bear Naked for over $60 million.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Flatley and Synnott stayed for a year to make a smooth transition to the new parent company.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Today, Kellogg's Kashi Co. organic unit manages the Bear Naked brand, from La Jolla, California.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] For its initial design, Bear Naked used a logo with three slashes suggesting bear claw marks.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] They chose a bear symbol because of its appetite for nuts, fruit, and honey.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] After a redesign in 2015, “Kevin” the bear was introduced.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] He now appears on all packaging, social media, and the company website.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] The new design uses orange, the signature color of Bear Naked's flagship Fruit and Nut granola.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] The color is meant to be energetic and hopes to appeal to millennials and others with active lives.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] Bear Naked's marketing strategy included presenting its product in a resealable cellophane pouch with a transparent window.
[src:apple-jacks/bear-naked] In 2019, Bear Naked made its stand-up pouch from 100% recyclable materials.
[src:apple-jacks/bran-buds] It used to be available in the United Kingdom during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:apple-jacks/bran-buds] The cereal was available in Ireland until the mid-1980s.
[src:apple-jacks/bran-buds] A serving of 1/3 cup (30 g) has 70 calories (293 kJ), 1 g of fat, 24 g of carbohydrates, 7 g sugar, and 2g of protein.
[src:apple-jacks/bran-buds] It contains 13 g of fiber (3 g soluble, 10 g insoluble).
[src:apple-jacks/bran-buds] Wheat bran, sugar/glucose-fructose, psyllium seed husks, corn bran (USA only), salt, baking soda, natural colour, vitamins (USA only, thiamin hydrochloride, d-calcium pantothenate, pyridoxine hydrochloride, folic acid, iron), BHT.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Although warm, cooked cereals like oat meal, maize grits, and wheat farina have the longest history as traditional breakfast foods, branded and *ready-to-eat cold cereals* (many produced via the process of extrusion) appeared around the late 19th century.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] These processed, precooked, packaged cereals are most often served in a quick and simple preparation with dairy products, traditionally cow's milk.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] These modern cereals can also be paired with yoghurt or plant-based milks, or eaten plain.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Fruit or nuts are sometimes added, and may enhance the nutritional benefits.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Some companies promote their products for the health benefits that come from eating oat-based and high-fiber cereals.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In the United States, cereals are often fortified with vitamins, but can still lack many of the vitamins needed for a healthful breakfast, and so initial marketing focused on making the new products "part of a complete breakfast".
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] A significant proportion of packaged cereals have a high sugar content ("sugar cereals" or even "kids' cereals" in common parlance).
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] These cereals are frequently marketed toward children (in television ads, comic books, etc.) and often feature a cartoon mascot and may contain a toy or prize.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Between 1970 and 1998, the number of different types of breakfast cereals in the United States more than doubled, from about 160 to around 340; as of 2012, there were roughly 5,000 different types (estimate based on the mass customization of online shopping).
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In this highly competitive market, cereal companies have developed an ever-increasing number of varieties and flavors (some are flavored like dessert or candy).
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Although many plain wheat-, oat- and corn-based cereals exist, a great many other varieties are highly sweetened, and some brands include freeze-dried fruit as a sweet element.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The breakfast cereal industry has gross profit margins of 40–45%, In 2009, market researchers expected the market to grow at a CAGR of 7.4% (in the next 5 years); it has had steady and continued growth throughout its history.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Cereal grains, namely porridge (and especially oatmeal), became an important breakfast component in North America.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Barley was a commonly used grain, though other grains and yellow peas could be used.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In many modern cultures, porridge is still eaten as a breakfast dish.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Native Americans had found a way to make ground corn palatable, later called *grits* (from the Old English word *grēot*, meaning "gravel").
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] While this became a staple in the southern U.S., grits never gained popularity in the northern states.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Food reformers in the 19th century called for cutting back on excessive meat consumption at breakfast.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] They explored numerous vegetarian alternatives.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Late in the century, the Seventh-day Adventists based in Michigan made these food reforms part of their religion, and non-meat breakfasts were featured in their sanitariums and led to new breakfast cereals.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Ferdinand Schumacher, a German immigrant, began the cereals revolution in 1854 with a hand oats grinder in the back room of a small store in Akron, Ohio.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] His German Mills American Oatmeal Company was the nation's first commercial oatmeal manufacturer.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] He marketed the product locally as a substitute for breakfast pork.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Improved production technology (steel cutters, porcelain rollers, improved hullers), combined with an influx of German and Irish immigrants, quickly boosted sales and profits.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1877, Schumacher adopted the Quaker symbol, the first registered trademark for a breakfast cereal.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The acceptance of "horse food" for human consumption encouraged other entrepreneurs to enter the industry.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Henry Parsons Crowell started operations in 1882, and John Robert Stuart in 1885.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Crowell cut costs by consolidating every step of the processing—grading, cleaning, hulling, cutting, rolling, packaging, and shipping—in one factory operating at Ravenna, Ohio.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Stuart operated mills in Chicago and Cedar Rapids, Iowa.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Stuart and Crowell combined in 1885 and initiated a price war.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] After a fire at his mill in Akron, Schumacher joined Stuart and Crowell to form the Consolidated Oatmeal Company.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The American Cereal Company (Quaker Oats, but see below) created a cereal made from oats in 1877, manufacturing the product in Akron, Ohio.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Separately, in 1888, a trust or holding company combined the nation's seven largest mills into the American Cereal Company using the Quaker Oats brand name.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] By 1900, technology, entrepreneurship, and the "Man in Quaker Garb"—a symbol of plain honesty and reliability—gave Quaker Oats a national market and annual sales of $10 million (equivalent to $390 million today).
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Early in the 20th century, the Quaker Oats Company (formed in 1901 to replace the American Cereal Company) ventured into the world market.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Schumacher, the innovator; Stuart, the manager and financial leader; and Crowell, the creative merchandiser, advertiser, and promoter, doubled sales every decade.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Anderson's steam-pressure method of shooting rice from guns created puffed rice and puffed wheat.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Crowell's intensive advertising campaign in the 1920s and 1930s featured promotions with such celebrities as Babe Ruth, Max Baer, and Shirley Temple.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Sponsorship of the popular *Rin-Tin-Tin* and *Sergeant Preston of the Yukon* radio shows aided the company's expansion during the depression.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Meat rationing during World War II boosted annual sales to $90 million (equivalent to $1.6 billion today), and by 1956 sales topped $277 million ($3.3 billion today).
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] By 1964 the firm sold over 200 products, grossed over $500 million ($5.2 billion today), and claimed that eight million people ate Quaker Oats each day.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Expansion included the acquisition of Aunt Jemima Mills Company in 1926, which continues as a leading brand of pancake mixes and syrup, the sport drink Gatorade in 1983, and in 1986, the Golden Grain Company, producers of Rice-A-Roni canned lunch food.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 2001, Quaker Oats was itself bought out by PepsiCo.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The first cold breakfast cereal, Granula, was invented in the United States in 1863 by James Caleb Jackson, operator of Our Home on the Hillside which was later replaced by the Jackson Sanatorium in Dansville, New York.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The cereal never became popular, due to the inconvenient necessity of tenderizing the heavy bran and graham nuggets by soaking them overnight.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Hoyt created Wheatena circa 1879, during an era when retailers would typically buy cereal (the most popular being cracked wheat, oatmeal, and cerealine) in barrel lots, and scoop it out to sell by the pound to customers.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Hoyt, who had found a distinctive process of preparing wheat for cereal, sold his cereal in boxes, offering consumers a more sanitary and consumer-friendly option.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Packaged breakfast cereals were considerably more convenient than a product that had to be cooked, and as a result of this convenience (and marketing that emphasized the point), they became popular.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Battle Creek, Michigan, was a center both of the Seventh-day Adventist Church and of innovation in the ready-to-eat cereal industry, and indeed, the church had a substantial impact on the development of cereal goods through the person of John Harvey Kellogg (1851–1943).
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Son of an Adventist factory owner in Battle Creek, Kellogg was encouraged by his church to train in medicine at Bellevue Hospital Medical College in New York City in 1875.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] After graduating, he became medical superintendent at the Western Health Reform Institute in Battle Creek, established in 1866 by the Adventists to offer their natural remedies for illness.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Many wealthy industrialists came to Kellogg's sanitarium for recuperation and rejuvenation.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In Battle Creek sanitarium guests found fresh air, exercise, rest, hydrotherapy, a strict vegetarian diet, and abstinence from alcohol, tobacco, coffee, and tea.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] (They were accustomed to breakfasts of ham, eggs, sausages, fried potatoes, hot biscuits, hotcakes (pancakes), and coffee.) To supplement the center's vegetarian regimen, Kellogg experimented with granola.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Soon afterwards he began to experiment with wheat, resulting in a lighter, flakier product.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1891 he acquired a patent and then in 1895 he launched the Cornflakes brand, which overnight captured a national market.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Soon there were forty rival manufacturers in the Battle Creek area.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Kellogg (1860–1951) worked for him for many years until, in 1906, he broke away, bought the rights to Cornflakes, and set up the Kellogg Toasted Corn Flake Company.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] William Kellogg discarded the health food concept, opting for heavy advertising and commercial taste appeal.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Later, his signature on every package became the company trademark.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The second major innovator in the cereal industry was Charles W.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Post, a salesman who was admitted to Kellogg's sanitarium as a patient in the late 1800s.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] While there, he grew deeply impressed with their all-grain diet.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Upon his release, he began experimenting with grain products, beginning with an all-grain coffee substitute called Postum.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1897 (or 1898) he introduced Grape-nuts, the concentrated cereal with a nutty flavor (containing neither grapes nor nuts).
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Good business sense, determination, and powerful advertising produced a multimillion-dollar fortune for Post in a few years.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] After his death, his company acquired the Jell-O company in 1925, Baker's Chocolate in 1927, Maxwell House coffee in 1928, and Birdseye frozen foods in 1929.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1929, the company changed its name to General Foods.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1985, Philip Morris Tobacco Company bought General Foods for $5.6 billion (equivalent to $16.8 billion today) and merged it with its Kraft division.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Because of Kellogg and Post, the city of Battle Creek, Michigan, is nicknamed the "Cereal Capital of the World".
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Muesli is a breakfast cereal based on uncooked rolled oats, fruit, and nuts.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] It was developed around 1900 by the Swiss physician Maximilian Bircher-Benner for patients in his hospital.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1902, Force wheat flakes became the first ready-to-eat breakfast cereal introduced into the United Kingdom.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The cereal, and the Sunny Jim character, achieved wide success in Britain, at its peak in 1930 selling 12.5 million packages in one year.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Kellogg began the breakfast cereal marketing and introduced the first in-box prize in the early 1900s.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Quaker Oats entered the market with Puffed Rice and Wheat Berries it had introduced at the 1904 World Fair, with raw grains shot with hot compressed air from tubes, popping up to many times their size.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] They were marketed as a revolution in food science.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In the 1920s, national advertising in magazines and radio broadcasts played a key role in the emergence of the fourth big cereal manufacturer, General Mills.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1921, James Ford Bell, president of a Minneapolis wheat milling firm, began experimenting with rolled wheat flakes.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] After tempering, steaming, cracking wheat, and processing it with syrup, sugar, and salt, it was prepared in a pressure cooker for rolling and then dried in an electric oven.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] By 1925, Wheaties had become the "Breakfast of Champions".
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1928, four milling companies consolidated as the General Mills Company in Minneapolis.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The new firm expanded packaged food sales with heavy advertising, including sponsorship of radio programs such as "Skippy", "Jack Armstrong, The All-American Boy", and baseball games.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Jack Dempsey, Johnny Weissmuller, and others verified the "Breakfast of Champions" slogan.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] By 1941 Wheaties had won 12% percent of the cereal market.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Experiments with the puffing process produced Kix, a puffed corn cereal, and Cheerios, a puffed oats cereal.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Further product innovation and diversification brought total General Mills sales to over $500 million annually (18% in packaged foods) by the early 1950s.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In 1944 General Foods launched a marketing campaign for Grape Nuts, focusing on nutritional importance of breakfast.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] After World War II, the big breakfast cereal companies—now including General Mills, who entered the market in 1924 with Wheaties—increasingly started to target children.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The flour was refined to remove fiber, which at the time was considered to undermine digestion and absorption of nutrients, and sugar was added to improve the flavor for children.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The new breakfast cereals began to look starkly different from their ancestors.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Ranger Joe, the first pre-sweetened breakfast cereal of sugar-coated puffed wheat or rice, was introduced in the US in 1939.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Kellogg's Sugar Smacks, created in 1953, had 56% sugar by weight.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Different mascots were introduced, such as the Rice Krispies elves and later pop icons like Tony the Tiger and the Trix Rabbit.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] A January 2025 study in the American Journal of Preventive Medicine examined cereal purchases from 77,000 American households over nine years alongside Nielsen ratings data on advertising exposure.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The study found that ads targeting adults had negligible impact, while those aimed at children strongly correlated with increased purchases of sugary cereals in households with kids.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Nine cereals, each with 9 to 12 grams of sugar per serving, dominated the market, accounting for 41% of total cereal bought.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In the 1960s, the modern version of granola was invented and popularized.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] It evolved from a product called Granula (similar to Grape Nuts) to the recognizable modern form involving at a minimum: sweetened toasted oats, but also possibly: dried fruit, puffed rice, nuts or chocolate.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Over 2016 to 2017, Americans purchased 3.1 billion boxes of cereal, mostly as ready to eat cold cereal.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] In a $9.8 billion cereal market, cold cereal purchases were 88% of the total (12% for hot cereals), with the overall cereal market declining due to reduced consumption of sugar and dairy products.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Kellogg's and General Mills each had 30% of the market share for cold cereals.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Honey Nut Cheerios was the leading cold cereal.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] The processing of grains helps to separate the bran and cereal germ, but may remove nutrients, such as B vitamins and dietary fiber.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Processing is the modification of a grain or mixture of grains usually taking place in a facility remote from the location where the product is eaten.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] This distinguishes "breakfast cereals" from foods made from grains modified and cooked in the place where they are eaten.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Breakfast cereals may be fortified with dietary minerals and vitamins.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] For example, breakfast cereal in Canada may be fortified with specific micronutrient amounts per 100 grams of cereal, including thiamin, (2.0 mg), niacin (4.8 mg), and vitamin B6 (0.6 mg), among others.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Consumption of breakfast cereal is under preliminary research for the potential to improve nutrition and affect chronic diseases.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Regular breakfast cereal consumption is associated with less risk of being overweight or obese and high-fiber breakfast cereals are associated with a lower risk of diabetes.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] Fortified breakfast cereals with iron can be an effective option to reduce risk of anemia in children.
[src:apple-jacks/breakfast-cereal] All images show the final preparation of the named (or described) cereal in a bowl with cow's milk and a spoon, unless stated otherwise.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples have continuously inhabited what is now Canada for thousands of years.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Beginning in the 16th century, British and French expeditions explored and later settled along the Atlantic coast.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] As a consequence of various armed conflicts, France ceded nearly all of its colonies in North America in 1763.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1867, with the union of three British North American colonies through Confederation, Canada was formed as a federal dominion of four provinces.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This began an accretion of provinces and territories resulting in the displacement of Indigenous populations, and a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This increased sovereignty was highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and culminated in the *Canada Act 1982*, which severed the vestiges of legal dependence on the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is a parliamentary democracy and a constitutional monarchy in the Westminster tradition.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country's head of government is the prime minister, who holds office by virtue of their ability to command the confidence of the elected House of Commons and is appointed by the governor general, representing the monarch of Canada, the ceremonial head of state.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country is a Commonwealth realm and is officially bilingual (English and French) in the federal jurisdiction.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It is very highly ranked in international measurements of government transparency, quality of life, economic competitiveness, innovation, education and human rights.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It is one of the world's most ethnically diverse and multicultural nations, the product of large-scale immigration.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's long and complex relationship with the United States has had a significant impact on its history, economy, and culture.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] A developed country, Canada's advanced economy has a high nominal per capita GDP globally and ranks among the largest in the world by nominal GDP, relying chiefly upon its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade networks.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power; its support for multilateralism and internationalism has been closely related to its foreign policies of peacekeeping and aid for developing countries.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participation in multiple international organizations and forums.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] While a variety of theories have been postulated for the etymological origins of *Canada*, the name is now accepted as coming from the St.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Lawrence Iroquoian word *kanata*, meaning 'village' or 'settlement'.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1535, Indigenous inhabitants of the present-day Quebec City region used the word to direct French explorer Jacques Cartier to the village of Stadacona.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Cartier later used the word *Canada* to refer not only to that particular village but to the entire area subject to Donnacona (the chief at Stadacona); by 1545, European books and maps had begun referring to this small region along the Saint Lawrence River as *Canada*.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] From the 16th to the early 18th century, *Canada* referred to the part of New France that lay along the Saint Lawrence River.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Following the British conquest of New France, this area was known as the British Province of Quebec from 1763 to 1791.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1791, the area became two British colonies called Upper Canada and Lower Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] These two colonies were collectively referred to as the Canadas until their union as the Province of Canada in 1841.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Upon Confederation in 1867, *Canada* was adopted as the legal name for the new country at the London Conference and the word *dominion* was conferred as the country's title, reflecting its status as a self-governing nation within the British Empire.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Following the London Declaration of 1949, where it was agreed that India could be a full member of the Commonwealth as a republic, not a dominion, the leaders of the Commonwealth countries agreed that the other members of the Commonwealth should not continue to be referred to as *dominions*.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Laurent announced in the Canadian House of Commons that in light of the *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, and the changes to the Commonwealth, *dominion* was no longer an accurate term to use to refer to Canada and would no longer be used by the federal government.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Similarly, the United Kingdom no longer used the term *dominions* to refer to Canada or other members of the Commonwealth, instead beginning to use the term a *realm of the Commonwealth*.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The *Canada Act 1982*, which brought the Constitution of Canada fully under Canadian control, referred only to *Canada*.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Later that year, the name of the national holiday was changed from Dominion Day to Canada Day.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The first inhabitants of North America are generally hypothesized to have migrated from Siberia by way of the Bering land bridge and arrived at least 14,000 years ago.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Paleo-Indian archeological sites at Old Crow Flats and Bluefish Caves are two of the oldest sites of human habitation in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The characteristics of Indigenous societies included permanent settlements, agriculture, complex societal hierarchies, and trading networks.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Some of these cultures had collapsed by the time European explorers arrived in the late 15th and early 16th centuries and have only been discovered through archeological investigations.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Indigenous peoples in present-day Canada include the First Nations, Inuit, and Métis, the last being of mixed descent who originated in the mid-17th century when First Nations people married European settlers and their offspring subsequently developed their own identity.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Indigenous population at the time of the first European settlements is estimated to have been between 200,000 and two million, with a figure of 500,000 accepted by Canada's Royal Commission on Aboriginal Peoples.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] As a consequence of European colonization, the Indigenous population declined by forty to eighty percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Although not without conflict, European Canadians' early interactions with First Nations and Inuit populations were relatively peaceful.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] First Nations and Métis peoples played a critical part in the development of European colonies in Canada, particularly for their role in assisting European coureurs des bois and voyageurs in their explorations of the continent during the North American fur trade.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] These early European interactions with First Nations would change from friendship and peace treaties to the dispossession of Indigenous lands through treaties.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] From the late 18th century, European Canadians forced Indigenous peoples to assimilate into a western Canadian society.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Settler colonialism reached a climax in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] A period of redress began with the formation of a reconciliation commission by the Government of Canada in 2008.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This included acknowledgment of cultural genocide, settlement agreements, and betterment of racial discrimination issues, such as addressing the plight of missing and murdered Indigenous women.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It is believed that the first documented European to explore the east coast of Canada was Norse explorer Leif Erikson.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In approximately 1000 AD, the Norse built a small short-lived encampment that was occupied sporadically for perhaps 20 years at L'Anse aux Meadows on the northern tip of Newfoundland.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] No further European exploration occurred until 1497, when seafarer John Cabot explored and claimed Canada's Atlantic coast in the name of Henry VII of England.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1534, French explorer Jacques Cartier explored the Gulf of Saint Lawrence where, on July 24, he planted a 10-metre (33 ft) cross bearing the words, "long live the King of France", and took possession of the territory New France in the name of King Francis I.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The early 16th century saw European mariners with navigational techniques pioneered by the Basque and Portuguese establish seasonal whaling and fishing outposts along the Atlantic coast.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In general, early settlements during the Age of Discovery appear to have been short-lived due to a combination of the harsh climate, problems with navigating trade routes and competing outputs in Scandinavia.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1583, Sir Humphrey Gilbert, by the royal prerogative of Queen Elizabeth I, founded St John's, Newfoundland, as the first North American English seasonal camp.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1600, the French established their first seasonal trading post at Tadoussac along the Saint Lawrence.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] French explorer Samuel de Champlain arrived in 1603 and established the first permanent year-round European settlements at Port Royal (in 1605) and Quebec City (in 1608).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Among the colonists of New France, *Canadiens* extensively settled the Saint Lawrence River valley and Acadians settled the present-day Maritimes, while fur traders and Catholic missionaries explored the Great Lakes, Hudson Bay, and the Mississippi watershed to Louisiana.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Beaver Wars broke out in the mid-17th century over control of the North American fur trade.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The English established additional settlements in Newfoundland in 1610 along with settlements in the Thirteen Colonies to the south.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] A series of four wars erupted in colonial North America between 1689 and 1763; the later wars of the period constituted the North American theatre of the Seven Years' War.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Mainland Nova Scotia came under British rule with the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht and Canada and most of New France came under British rule in 1763 after the Seven Years' War.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 established First Nation treaty rights, created the Province of Quebec out of New France, and annexed Cape Breton Island to Nova Scotia.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] St John's Island (now Prince Edward Island) became a separate colony in 1769.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] To avert conflict in Quebec, the British Parliament passed the Quebec Act 1774, expanding Quebec's territory to the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] More importantly, the Quebec Act afforded Quebec special autonomy and rights of self-administration at a time when the Thirteen Colonies were increasingly agitating against British rule.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It re-established the French language, Catholic faith, and French civil law there, staving off the growth of an independence movement in contrast to the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Proclamation and the Quebec Act in turn angered many residents of the Thirteen Colonies, further fuelling anti-British sentiment in the years prior to the American Revolution.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] After the American War of Independence, the 1783 Treaty of Paris recognized the independence of the United States and set the terms of peace, ceding British North American territories south of the Great Lakes and east of the Mississippi River to the new country.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The American war of independence also caused a large out-migration of Loyalists, the settlers who had fought against American independence.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Many moved to Canada, particularly Atlantic Canada, where their arrival changed the demographic distribution of the existing territories.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] New Brunswick was in turn split from Nova Scotia as part of a reorganization of Loyalist settlements in the Maritimes, which led to the incorporation of Saint John, New Brunswick, as Canada's first city.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] To accommodate the influx of English-speaking Loyalists in Central Canada, the Constitutional Act of 1791 divided the province of Canada into French-speaking Lower Canada (later Quebec) and English-speaking Upper Canada (later Ontario), granting each its own elected legislative assembly.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Canadas were the main front in the War of 1812 between the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Peace came in 1815; no boundaries were changed.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Immigration resumed at a higher level, with over 960,000 arrivals from Britain between 1815 and 1850.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] New arrivals included refugees escaping the Great Irish Famine as well as Gaelic-speaking Scots displaced by the Highland Clearances.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Infectious diseases killed between 25 and 33 percent of Europeans who immigrated to Canada before 1891.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The desire for responsible government resulted in the abortive Rebellions of 1837.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Durham Report subsequently recommended responsible government and the assimilation of French Canadians into English culture.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Act of Union 1840 merged the Canadas into a united Province of Canada and responsible government was established for all provinces of British North America east of Lake Superior by 1855.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The signing of the Oregon Treaty by Britain and the United States in 1846 ended the Oregon boundary dispute, extending the border westward along the 49th parallel.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This paved the way for British colonies on Vancouver Island (1849) and in British Columbia (1858).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Anglo-Russian Treaty of Saint Petersburg (1825) established the border along the Pacific coast, but, even after the US Alaska Purchase of 1867, disputes continued about the exact demarcation of the Alaska–Yukon and Alaska–British Columbia border.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Following three constitutional conferences, the *British North America Act, 1867* officially proclaimed Canadian Confederation on July 1, 1867, initially with four provinces: Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada assumed control of Rupert's Land and the North-Western Territory to form the Northwest Territories, where the Métis' grievances ignited the Red River Rebellion and the creation of the province of Manitoba in July 1870.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] British Columbia and Vancouver Island (which had been united in 1866) joined the confederation in 1871 on the promise of a transcontinental railway extending to Victoria in the province within 10 years, while Prince Edward Island joined in 1873.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1898, during the Klondike Gold Rush in the Northwest Territories, Parliament created the Yukon Territory.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Alberta and Saskatchewan became provinces in 1905.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Between 1871 and 1896, almost one quarter of the Canadian population emigrated south to the US.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] To settle the West and attract European immigrants, Canada sponsored the construction of three transcontinental railways, enacted the *Dominion Lands Act* and founded the North-West Mounted Police to maintain regional authority.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This period of westward expansion and nation building resulted in the displacement of many Indigenous peoples of the Canadian Prairies to "Indian reserves", clearing the way for ethnic European block settlements.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This caused the collapse of the Plains Bison in western Canada and the introduction of European cattle farms and wheat fields dominating the land.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Indigenous peoples saw widespread famine and disease due to the loss of the bison and their traditional hunting lands.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The federal government did provide emergency relief, on condition of the Indigenous peoples moving to the reserves.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] During this time, Canada introduced the *Indian Act* extending its control over the First Nations to education, government and legal rights.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Because Britain still maintained control of Canada's foreign affairs under the British North America Act, 1867, its declaration of war in 1914 automatically brought Canada into the First World War.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Volunteers sent to the Western Front later became part of the Canadian Corps, which played a substantial role in the Battle of Vimy Ridge and other major engagements of the war.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Conscription Crisis of 1917 erupted when the Unionist Cabinet's proposal to augment the military's dwindling number of active members with conscription was met with vehement objections from French-speaking Quebecers.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1919, Canada joined the League of Nations independently of Britain.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Great Depression in Canada during the early 1930s saw an economic downturn, leading to hardship across the country.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In response to the downturn, the Co-operative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) in Saskatchewan introduced many elements of a welfare state (as pioneered by Tommy Douglas) in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] On the advice of Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, war with Germany was declared effective September 10, 1939, by King George VI, seven days after the United Kingdom.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The delay underscored Canada's independence.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The first Canadian Army units arrived in Britain in December 1939.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In all, over a million Canadians served in the armed forces during the Second World War.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canadian troops played important roles in many key battles of the war, including the failed 1942 Dieppe Raid, the Allied invasion of Italy, the Normandy landings, the Battle of Normandy, and the Battle of the Scheldt in 1944.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada provided asylum for the Dutch monarchy while that country was occupied and is credited by the Netherlands for major contributions to its liberation from Nazi Germany.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Despite another conscription crisis in Quebec in 1944, Canada finished the war with a large army and strong economy.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The financial crisis of the Great Depression led the Dominion of Newfoundland to relinquish responsible government in 1934 and become a Crown colony ruled by a British governor.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] After two referendums, Newfoundlanders voted to join Canada in 1949 as a province.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Socially democratic programs were also instituted, such as Medicare, the Canada Pension Plan, and Canada Student Loans; though, provincial governments, particularly Quebec and Alberta, opposed many of these as incursions into their jurisdictions.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Finally, another series of constitutional conferences resulted in the *Canada Act 1982*, the patriation of Canada's constitution from the United Kingdom, concurrent with the creation of the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada had established complete sovereignty as an independent country under its own monarchy.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1999, Nunavut became Canada's third territory after a series of negotiations with the federal government.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] At the same time, Quebec underwent profound social and economic changes through the Quiet Revolution of the 1960s, giving birth to a secular nationalist movement.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The radical Front de libération du Québec (FLQ) ignited the October Crisis with a series of bombings and kidnappings in 1970, and the sovereigntist Parti Québécois was elected in 1976, organizing an unsuccessful referendum on sovereignty-association in 1980.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Attempts to accommodate Quebec nationalism constitutionally through the Meech Lake Accord failed in 1990.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This led to the formation of the Bloc Québécois in Quebec and the invigoration of the Reform Party of Canada in the West.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] A second referendum followed in 1995, in which sovereignty was rejected by a slimmer margin of 50.6 to 49.4 percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 1997, the Supreme Court ruled unilateral secession by a province would be unconstitutional, and the Clarity Act was passed by Parliament, outlining the terms of a negotiated departure from Confederation.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In addition to the issues of Quebec sovereignty, a number of crises shook Canadian society in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada joined the Gulf War in 1990 and was active in several peacekeeping missions in the 1990s, including operations in the Balkans during and after the Yugoslav Wars, and in Somalia, resulting in an incident that has been described as "the darkest era in the history of the Canadian military".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] After the September 11 attacks in the United States, Canada sent troops to Afghanistan in 2001, resulting in the largest amount of Canadian deaths for any single military mission since the Korean War in the early 1950s.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 2011, Canadian forces participated in the NATO-led intervention into the Libyan Civil War and also became involved in battling the Islamic State insurgency in Iraq in the mid-2010s.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic in Canada began on January 27, 2020, causing widespread social and economic disruption.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 2021, possible gravesites of Indigenous children were found near former Canadian residential schools, highlighting the cultural genocide against Indigenous peoples.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] A trade war involving the United States began on February 1, 2025, when U.S. president Donald Trump signed orders imposing tariffs on goods entering the United States, alongside rhetoric suggesting the annexation of Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] By total area (including its waters), Canada is the second-largest country.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] By land area alone, Canada ranks fourth, due to having the world's largest area of fresh water lakes.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Stretching from the Atlantic Ocean in the east, along the Arctic Ocean to the north, and to the Pacific Ocean in the west, the country encompasses 9,984,670 square kilometres (3,855,100 sq mi) of territory.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is also home to the world's northernmost settlement, Canadian Forces Station Alert, on the northern tip of Ellesmere Island—latitude 82.5°N—which lies 817 kilometres (508 mi) from the North Pole.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In latitude, Canada's most northerly point of land is Cape Columbia in Nunavut at 83°6′41″N, with its southern extreme at Middle Island in Lake Erie at 41°40′53″N.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In longitude, Canada's land extends from Cape Spear, Newfoundland, at 52°37′W, to Mount St.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada can be divided into seven physiographic regions: the Canadian Shield, the Interior Plains, the Great Lakes–St.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Lawrence Lowlands, the Appalachian region, the Western Cordillera, Hudson Bay Lowlands, and the Arctic Archipelago.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Boreal forests prevail throughout the country, ice is prominent in northern Arctic regions and through the Rocky Mountains, and the relatively flat Canadian Prairies in the southwest facilitate productive agriculture.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Lawrence River (in the southeast) where the lowlands host much of Canada's economic output.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has over 2,000,000 lakes—563 of which are larger than 100 square kilometres (39 sq mi)—containing much of the world's fresh water.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] There are also fresh-water glaciers in the Canadian Rockies, the Coast Mountains, and the Arctic Cordillera.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is geologically active, having many earthquakes and potentially active volcanoes.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Average winter and summer high temperatures across Canada vary from region to region.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Winters can be harsh in many parts of the country, particularly in the interior and Prairie provinces, which experience a continental climate, where daily average temperatures are near −15 °C (5 °F), but can drop below −40 °C (−40 °F) with severe wind chills.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In non-coastal regions, snow can cover the ground for almost six months of the year, while in parts of the north snow can persist year-round.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Coastal British Columbia has a temperate climate, with a mild and rainy winter.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] On the east and west coasts, average high temperatures are generally in the low 20s °C (70s °F), while between the coasts, the average summer high temperature ranges from 25 to 30 °C (77 to 86 °F), with temperatures in some interior locations occasionally exceeding 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Much of Northern Canada is covered by ice and permafrost.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The future of the permafrost is uncertain because the Arctic has been warming at three times the global average as a result of climate change in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's annual average temperature over land has risen by 1.7 °C (3.1 °F), with changes ranging from 1.1 to 2.3 °C (2.0 to 4.1 °F) in various regions, since 1948.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The rate of warming has been higher across the North and in the Prairies.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In the southern regions of Canada, air pollution from both Canada and the United States—caused by metal smelting, burning coal to power utilities, and vehicle emissions—has resulted in acid rain, which has severely impacted waterways, forest growth, and agricultural productivity.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is one of the largest greenhouse gas emitters globally, with emissions increased by 16.5 percent between 1990 and 2022.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is divided into 15 terrestrial and five marine ecozones.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] These ecozones encompass over 80,000 classified species of Canadian wildlife, with an equal number yet to be formally recognized or discovered.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Although Canada has a low percentage of endemic species compared to other countries, due to human activities, invasive species, and environmental issues in the country, there are currently more than 800 species at risk of being lost.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] About 65 percent of Canada's resident species are considered "Secure".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Over half of Canada's landscape is intact and relatively free of human development.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The boreal forest of Canada is considered to be the largest intact forest on Earth, with approximately 3,000,000 square kilometres (1,200,000 sq mi) undisturbed by roads, cities or industry.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Since the end of the last glacial period, Canada has consisted of eight distinct forest regions.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Approximately 12.1 percent of the nation's landmass and freshwater are conservation areas, including 11.4 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Approximately 13.8 percent of its territorial waters are conserved, including 8.9 percent designated as protected areas.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's first National Park, Banff National Park was established in 1885.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's oldest provincial park, Algonquin Provincial Park was established in 1893.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Established in 2015, Lake Superior National Marine Conservation Area is the world's largest freshwater protected area.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's largest national wildlife region, established in 2018, is the Scott Islands Marine National Wildlife Area.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is described as a "full democracy", with a tradition of liberalism, and an egalitarian, moderate political ideology.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Since the 1960s, an emphasis on social justice has been a distinguishing element of Canada's political culture.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Peace, order, and good government, alongside an Implied Bill of Rights, are founding principles of Canadian federalism.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] At the federal level, Canada has been dominated by two relatively centrist parties practising "brokerage politics": the centre-left leaning Liberal Party of Canada and the centre-right leaning Conservative Party of Canada (or its predecessors).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The historically predominant Liberals position themselves at the centre of the political scale.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Far-right and far-left politics have never been a prominent force in Canadian society.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has a parliamentary system within the context of a constitutional monarchy—the monarchy of Canada being the foundation of the executive, legislative, and judicial branches.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The reigning monarch is also monarch of 14 other sovereign Commonwealth countries and Canada's 10 provinces.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The monarch appoints a representative, the governor general, on the advice of the prime minister, to carry out most of their ceremonial royal duties.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The monarchy is the source of sovereignty and authority in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] To ensure the stability of government, the governor general will usually appoint as prime minister the person who is the current leader of the political party that can obtain the confidence of a majority of members in the House.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The leader of the party with the second-most seats usually becomes the leader of the Official Opposition and is part of an adversarial parliamentary system intended to keep the government in check.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Parliament of Canada passes all federal statute laws.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It comprises the monarch, the House of Commons, and the Senate.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] While Canada inherited the British concept of parliamentary supremacy, this was later, with the enactment of the Constitution Act, 1982, all but completely superseded by the American notion of the supremacy of the law.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Each of the 343 members of Parliament in the House of Commons is elected by simple plurality in an electoral district or riding.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The 105 members of the Senate, whose seats are apportioned on a regional basis, serve until age 75.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canadian federalism divides government responsibilities between the federal government and the 10 provinces.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Provincial legislatures are unicameral and operate in parliamentary fashion similar to the House of Commons.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's three territories also have legislatures, but these are not sovereign, have fewer constitutional responsibilities than the provinces, and differ structurally from their provincial counterparts.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Constitution of Canada is the supreme law of the country and consists of written text and unwritten conventions.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The *Constitution Act, 1867* (known as the British North America Act, 1867 prior to 1982), affirmed governance based on parliamentary precedent and divided powers between the federal and provincial governments.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The *Statute of Westminster, 1931*, granted full autonomy, and the *Constitution Act, 1982*, ended all legislative ties to Britain, as well as adding a constitutional amending formula and the *Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms*.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The *Charter* guarantees basic rights and freedoms that usually cannot be overridden by any government; a notwithstanding clause allows Parliament and the provincial legislatures to override certain sections of the *Charter* for a period of five years.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's judiciary interprets laws and has the power to strike down acts of Parliament that violate the constitution.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Supreme Court of Canada is the highest court, final arbiter, and has been led since 2017 by Richard Wagner, the Chief Justice of Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The governor general appoints the court's nine members on the advice of the prime minister and minister of justice.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The federal Cabinet also appoints justices to superior courts in the provincial and territorial jurisdictions.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Common law prevails everywhere except Quebec, where civil law predominates.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Criminal law is solely a federal responsibility and is uniform throughout Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Law enforcement, including criminal courts, is officially a provincial responsibility, conducted by provincial and municipal police forces.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In most rural and some urban areas, policing responsibilities are contracted to the federal Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canadian Aboriginal law provides certain constitutionally recognized rights to land and traditional practices for Indigenous groups in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Various treaties and case laws were established to mediate relations between Europeans and many Indigenous peoples.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The role of Aboriginal law and the rights they support were reaffirmed by section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] These rights may include provision of services, such as healthcare through the Indian Health Transfer Policy, and exemption from taxation.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is a federation composed of 10 federated states, called provinces, and three federal territories.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] These may be grouped into four main regions: Western Canada, Central Canada, Atlantic Canada, and Northern Canada (*Eastern Canada* refers to Central Canada and Atlantic Canada together).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Provinces and territories have responsibility for social programs such as healthcare, education, and social programs, as well as administration of justice (but not criminal law).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Although the provinces collect more revenue than the federal government, equalization payments are made by the federal government to ensure reasonably uniform standards of services and taxation are kept between the richer and poorer provinces.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is recognized as a middle power for its role in global affairs with a tendency to pursue multilateral and international solutions.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Globalization has significantly influenced Canadian foreign policies, with the country known for its promotion of peace and security through mediation, and for providing aid to developing countries.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada and the United States have a long and complex relationship; historically close allies, they co-operate regularly on military campaigns and humanitarian efforts.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada also maintains historic and traditional ties to the United Kingdom and to France, along with both countries' former colonies through its membership in the Commonwealth of Nations and the *Organisation internationale de la Francophonie*.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is noted for having a positive relationship with the Netherlands, owing, in part, to its contribution to the Dutch liberation during the Second World War.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has diplomatic and consular offices in over 270 locations in approximately 180 foreign countries.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada promotes its domestically shared values through participating in multiple international organizations.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada was a founding member of the United Nations (UN) in 1945 and formed the North American Aerospace Defense Command together with the United States in 1958.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country has membership in the World Trade Organization, the Five Eyes, the G7 and the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country was a founding member of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) in 1989 and joined the Organization of American States (OAS) in 1990.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada ratified the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) in 1948, and seven principal UN human rights conventions and covenants since then.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Alongside many domestic obligations, more than 3,000 Canadian Armed Forces (CAF) personnel are deployed in multiple foreign military operations.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Canadian unified forces comprise the Royal Canadian Navy, Canadian Army, and Royal Canadian Air Force.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The nation employs a professional, volunteer force of approximately 68,000 active personnel and 27,000 reserve personnel.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In March 2026, Canada achieved the NATO target of spending 2% of its GDP on defence for the 2026 fiscal year.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] This marks a significant increase from previous years—roughly 1.3% to 1.4% between 2021 and 2024.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's role in developing *peacekeeping* and its participation in initiatives during the 20th century has played a major role in its positive global image.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Peacekeeping is deeply embedded in Canadian culture and a distinguishing feature that Canadians feel sets their foreign policy apart from the United States.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has long been reluctant to participate in military interventions that are not sanctioned by the United Nations, such as the Vietnam War, the 2003 invasion of Iraq and 2026 Iran war.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Since the 21st century, Canadian direct participation in UN peacekeeping efforts has greatly declined.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The large decrease was a result of Canada directing its participation to UN-sanctioned military operations through the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, rather than directly through the UN.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The change to participation via NATO has resulted in a shift towards more militarized and deadly missions rather than traditional peacekeeping duties.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's mixed-market economy is highly developed, ranking as the world's ninth-largest by nominal GDP as of 2023, at approximately US$2.221 trillion.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country is one of the world's largest trading nations, with a highly globalized economy.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 2021, Canadian trade in goods and services reached $2.016 trillion.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's exports totalled over $637 billion, while its imported goods were worth over $631 billion, of which approximately $391 billion originated from the United States.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 2018, Canada had a trade deficit in goods of $22 billion and a trade deficit in services of $25 billion.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Toronto Stock Exchange is the ninth-largest stock exchange in the world by market capitalization, listing over 1,500 companies with a combined market capitalization of over US$2 trillion.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Bank of Canada is the central bank of the country.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The minister of finance and minister of innovation, science, and industry use data from Statistics Canada to enable financial planning and develop economic policy.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has a strong cooperative banking sector, with the world's highest per-capita membership in credit unions.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It ranks low in the Corruption Perceptions Index (14th in 2023) and "is widely regarded as among the least corrupt countries of the world".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It ranks high in the Global Competitiveness Report (19th in 2024).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's economy ranks above most Western nations on the Heritage Foundation's Index of Economic Freedom and experiences a relatively low level of income disparity.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country's average household disposable income per capita is "well above" the OECD average.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada ranks among the lowest of the most developed countries for housing affordability and foreign direct investment.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The unemployment rate in 2025 was 6.8 percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Since the early 20th century, the growth of Canada's manufacturing, mining, and service sectors has transformed the nation from a largely rural economy to an urbanized, industrial one.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Canadian economy is dominated by the service industry, which employs about three-quarters of the country's workforce.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has an unusually important primary sector, of which the forestry and petroleum industries are the most prominent components.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Many towns in northern Canada, where agriculture is difficult, are sustained by nearby mines or sources of timber.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's economic integration with the United States has increased significantly since the Second World War.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Canada – United States Free Trade Agreement (FTA) of 1988 eliminated tariffs between the two countries, while the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) expanded the free-trade zone to include Mexico in 1994 (later replaced by the Canada–United States–Mexico Agreement).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] As of 2023, Canada is a signatory to 15 free trade agreements with 51 different countries.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is one of the few developed nations that are net exporters of energy.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Atlantic Canada possess vast offshore deposits of natural gas, and Alberta hosts the fourth-largest oil reserves in the world.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The vast Athabasca oil sands and other oil reserves give Canada 13 percent of global oil reserves, constituting the world's third- or fourth-largest.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada is additionally one of the world's largest suppliers of agricultural products; the Canadian Prairies region is one of the most important global producers of wheat, canola, and other grains.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's main exports are zinc, uranium, gold, nickel, platinoids, aluminum, steel, iron ore, coking coal, lead, copper, molybdenum, cobalt, and cadmium.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has a sizeable manufacturing sector centred in southern Ontario and Quebec, with automobiles and aeronautics representing particularly important industries.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country's fishing and tourism industries are also a key contributor to the economy.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] In 2020, Canada spent approximately $41.9 billion on domestic research and development, with supplementary estimates for 2022 at $43.2 billion.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] As of 2023, the country has produced 15 Nobel laureates in physics, chemistry, and medicine.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The country ranks seventh in the worldwide share of articles published in scientific journals, according to the Nature Index, and is home to the headquarters of a number of global technology firms.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has one of the highest levels of Internet access in the world, with approximately 95 percent of its population aged 15 and above.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada's achievements in science and technology include the creation of the modern alkaline battery, the discovery of insulin, the development of the polio vaccine, and discoveries about the interior structure of the atomic nucleus.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Other major Canadian scientific contributions include the artificial cardiac pacemaker, mapping the visual cortex, the development of the electron microscope, plate tectonics, deep learning, multi-touch technology, and the identification of the first black hole, Cygnus X-1.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has a long history of discovery in genetics, which include stem cells, site-directed mutagenesis, T-cell receptor, and the identification of the genes that cause Fanconi anemia, cystic fibrosis, and early-onset Alzheimer's disease, among numerous other diseases.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] The Canadian Space Agency runs an active space program focused on deep-space, planetary, and aviation research, along with rockets and satellites.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada launched its first satellite, Alouette 1, in 1962.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] It contributes to the International Space Station and is known for its robotic tools, such as multiple Canadarms.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p01] Canada has initiated many long-term projects, including the Radarsat satellite series and the Black Brant rocket series.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The 2021 Canadian census enumerated a total population of 36,991,981, an increase of around 5.2 percent over the 2016 figure.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] It is estimated that Canada's population surpassed 40,000,000 in 2023.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The main drivers of population growth are immigration and, to a lesser extent, natural growth.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest per-capita immigration rates in the world, driven mainly by economic policy and family reunification.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] A record 483,390 immigrants were admitted in 2024.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada leads the world in refugee resettlement; it resettled more than 47,600 in 2022.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] New immigrants settle mostly in major urban areas, such as Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada's population density, at 4.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (11/sq mi), is among the lowest in the world, with approximately 95 percent of the population residing south of the 55th parallel north.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] About 80 percent of the population lives within 150 kilometres (93 mi) of the border with the contiguous United States.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada is highly urbanized, with over 80 percent of the population living in urban centres.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (over 70 percent) live below the 49th parallel, with 50 percent of Canadians living south of 45°42′ (45.7 degrees) north.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The most densely populated part of the country is the Quebec City–Windsor Corridor in Southern Quebec and Southern Ontario along the Great Lakes and the St.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The majority of Canadians (81.1 percent) live in family households, 12.1 percent report living alone, and 6.8 percent live with other relatives or unrelated persons.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Fifty-one percent of households are couples with or without children, 8.7 percent are single-parent households, 2.9 percent are multigenerational households, and 29.3 percent are single-person households.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Respondents in the 2021 Canadian census self-reported over 450 "ethnic or cultural origins".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Over 60 percent of Canadians reported a single origin, and 36 percent reported having multiple ethnic origins, thus the overall total is greater than 100 percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Of the 36.3 million people enumerated in 2021, approximately 25.4 million reported being "White", representing 69.8 percent of the population.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The Indigenous population representing 5 percent or 1.8 million people, grew by 9.4 percent compared to the non-Indigenous population, which grew by 5.3 percent from 2016 to 2021.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Between 2011 and 2016, the visible minority population rose by 18.4 percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In 1961, about 300,000 people, less than two percent of Canada's population, were members of visible minority groups.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The 2021 census indicated that 8.3 million people, or almost one-quarter (23.0 percent) of the population, reported themselves as being or having been a landed immigrant or permanent resident in Canada—above the 1921 census previous record of 22.3 percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In 2021, India, China, and the Philippines were the top three countries of origin for immigrants moving to Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] A multitude of languages are used by Canadians, with English and French (the official languages) being the mother tongues of approximately 54 percent and 19 percent of Canadians, respectively.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada's official bilingualism policies give citizens the right to receive federal government services in either English or French with official-language minorities guaranteed their own schools in all provinces and territories.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Quebec's 1974 *Official Language Act* established French as the only official language of the province.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Although more than 82 percent of French-speaking Canadians live in Quebec, there are substantial Francophone populations in New Brunswick, Alberta, and Manitoba, with Ontario having the largest French-speaking population outside Quebec.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] New Brunswick, the only officially bilingual province, has an Acadian French minority constituting 33 percent of the population.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] There are also clusters of Acadians in southwestern Nova Scotia, on Cape Breton Island, and in central and western Prince Edward Island.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Other provinces have no official languages as such, but French is used as a language of instruction, in courts, and for other government services, in addition to English.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Manitoba, Ontario, and Quebec allow for both English and French to be spoken in the provincial legislatures and laws are enacted in both languages.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In Ontario, French has some legal status, but is not fully co-official.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] There are 11 Indigenous language groups, composed of more than 65 distinct languages and dialects.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Several Indigenous languages have official status in the Northwest Territories.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Inuktitut is the majority language in Nunavut and is one of three official languages in the territory.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] As of the 2021 census, just over 7.8 million Canadians listed a non-official language as their first language.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The country is also home to many sign languages, some of which are Indigenous.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] American Sign Language (ASL) is used across the country due to the prevalence of ASL in primary and secondary schools.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Quebec Sign Language (LSQ) is used primarily in Quebec.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada is religiously diverse, encompassing a wide range of beliefs and customs.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The Constitution of Canada refers to God; however, Canada has no official church and the government is officially committed to religious pluralism.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Freedom of religion in Canada is a constitutionally protected right.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Rates of religious adherence have steadily decreased since the 1970s.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] With Christianity in decline after having once been central and integral to Canadian culture and daily life, Canada has become a post-Christian, secular state.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Although the majority of Canadians consider religion to be unimportant in their daily lives, they still believe in God.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The practice of religion is generally considered a private matter.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] According to the 2021 census, Christianity is the largest religion in Canada, with Roman Catholics representing 29.9 percent of the population having the most adherents.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Christians overall representing 53.3 percent of the population, are followed by people reporting irreligion or having no religion at 34.6 percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Other faiths include Islam (4.9 percent), Hinduism (2.3 percent), Sikhism (2.1 percent), Buddhism (1.0 percent), Judaism (0.9 percent), and Indigenous spirituality (0.2 percent).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada has the second-largest national Sikh population, behind India.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Healthcare in Canada is delivered through the provincial and territorial systems of publicly funded health care, informally called Medicare.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] It is guided by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984 and is universal.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Universal access to publicly funded health services "is often considered by Canadians as a fundamental value that ensures national healthcare insurance for everyone wherever they live in the country".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Around 30 percent of Canadians' healthcare is paid for through the private sector.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] This mostly pays for services not covered or partially covered by Medicare, such as prescription drugs, dentistry and optometry.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Approximately 65 to 75 percent of Canadians have some form of supplementary health insurance; many receive it through their employers or access secondary social service programs.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Canada is experiencing an increase in healthcare expenditures due to a demographic shift toward an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In 2021, the average age in Canada was 41.9 years.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] A 2016 report by the chief public health officer found that 88 percent of Canadians, one of the highest proportions of the population among G7 countries, indicated that they "had good or very good health".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Eighty percent of Canadian adults self-report having at least one major risk factor for chronic disease: smoking, physical inactivity, unhealthy eating or excessive alcohol use.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada has one of the highest rates of adult obesity among OECD countries, contributing to approximately 2.7 million cases of diabetes.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Four chronic diseases—cancer (leading cause of death), cardiovascular diseases, respiratory diseases, and diabetes—account for 65 percent of deaths in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] There are approximately 8 million people aged 15 and older with one or more disabilities in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In 2024, the Canadian Institute for Health Information estimated that healthcare spending reached $372 billion, or 12.4 percent of Canada's GDP for that year.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In 2022, Canada's per-capita spending on health expenditures ranked 12th among health-care systems in the OECD.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The Commonwealth Fund's 2021 report comparing the healthcare systems of the 11 most developed countries ranked Canada second-to-last.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Identified weaknesses were comparatively higher infant mortality rate, the prevalence of chronic conditions, long wait times, poor availability of after-hours care, and a lack of prescription drugs and dental coverage.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] An increasing problem in Canada's health system is a lack of healthcare professionals and hospital capacity.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Education in Canada is for the most part provided publicly, funded and overseen by federal, provincial, and local governments.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Education is within provincial jurisdiction and a province's curriculum is overseen by its government.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Education in Canada is generally divided into primary education, followed by secondary and post-secondary education.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Education in both English and French is available in most places across Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada has a large number of universities, almost all of which are publicly funded.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Established in 1663, Université Laval is the oldest post-secondary institution in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The nation's three top ranking universities are the University of Toronto, McGill, and the University of British Columbia.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The largest university is the University of Toronto, which has over 85,000 students.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] According to a 2022 report by the OECD, Canada is one of the most educated countries in the world; the country ranks first worldwide in the percentage of adults having tertiary education, with over 56 percent of Canadian adults having attained at least an undergraduate college or university degree.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada spends an average of 5.3 percent of its GDP on education.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The country invests heavily in tertiary education (more than US$20,000 per student).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] As of 2022, 89 percent of adults aged 25 to 64 have earned the equivalent of a high-school degree, compared to an OECD average of 75 percent.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada is influenced by British, French and Indigenous cultures and traditions.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] During the 20th century, Canadians with African, Caribbean, and Asian heritages have added to Canadian identity.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada's culture draws influences from its broad range of constituent nationalities, and policies that promote a just society are constitutionally protected.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Since the 1960s, Canada has emphasized human rights and inclusiveness for all its people.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian identity shifted from primarily British-based to multicultural between the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The official state policy of multiculturalism is often cited as one of Canada's significant accomplishments and a key distinguishing element of Canadian identity.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In Quebec, cultural identity is strong and there is a French Canadian culture that is distinct from English Canadian culture.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] As a whole, Canada is in theory a cultural mosaic of regional ethnic subcultures with diverse areas and ethnic enclaves.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada's approach to governance emphasizing multiculturalism, which is based on selective immigration, social integration, and suppression of far-right politics, has wide public support.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadians also identify with the country's foreign aid policies, peacekeeping roles, the national park system, and the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Themes of nature, pioneers, trappers, and traders played an important part in the early development of Canadian symbolism.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Modern symbols emphasize the country's geography, northern climate, lifestyles, and the Canadianization of traditional European and Indigenous symbols.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The use of the maple leaf as a symbol dates to the early 18th century in New France.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The maple leaf is depicted on Canada's current and previous flags and on the arms of Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada's official tartan, known as the "maple leaf tartan", reflects the colours of the maple leaf through the seasons—green in the spring, gold in the early autumn, red at the first frost, and brown after falling.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The arms of Canada are closely modelled after those of the United Kingdom, with French and distinctive Canadian elements replacing or added to those derived from the British version.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian cuisine items such as Canadian beer, maple syrup, Nanaimo bars, butter tarts, and the Quebec dishes of poutine and tourtière, alongside material items such as tuques, canoes and Hudson's Bay point blanket are considered as uniquely Canadian.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian coins feature many of these symbols: the loon on the $1 coin, the coat of arms on the 50¢ piece, and the beaver on the nickel.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] An image of the monarch appears on $20 bank notes and the obverse of coins.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian literature is often divided into French- and English-language literatures, which are rooted in the literary traditions of France and Britain, respectively.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The earliest Canadian narratives were of travel and exploration.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] This developed into three major themes of historical Canadian literature: nature, frontier life, and Canada's position within the world, all of which tie into the garrison mentality.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The evolution of Canadian literature is intricately linked to the country's historical and social contexts, often mirroring the challenges and changes in Canadian society.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] As Canadian literature progressed into the 20th and 21st centuries, it began to address a broader array of subjects and themes, such as women's rights, LGBTQ rights, immigrant experiences, environmental issues, the relationship with Indigenous peoples, and Canadian values and identity.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Financial support from governmental bodies, such as the Canada Council for the Arts and various provincial grant programs, facilitates the creation, publication, and promotion of works by Canadian authors.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Numerous Canadian authors have received international literary awards including the Nobel Prize in Literature, the Booker Prize, and the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian literary awards and prizes include the Governor General's Literary Awards, the Giller Prize, the Latner Griffin Writers' Trust Poetry Prize, the Burt Award for First Nations, Inuit and Métis Literature and several accolades for literature aimed at children.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Art in Canada is marked by thousands of years of habitation by Indigenous peoples, and, in later times, artists have combined British, French, Indigenous, and American artistic traditions, at times embracing European styles while working to promote nationalism.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The nature of Canadian art reflects these diverse origins, as artists have taken their traditions and adapted these influences to reflect the reality of their lives in Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The Group of Seven is often considered the first uniquely Canadian artistic group and style of painting.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Inuit art since the 1950s has been the traditional gift given to foreign dignitaries by the Canadian government.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Historically, the Catholic Church was the primary patron of art in early Canada, especially Quebec.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The Government of Canada has played a role in the development of art, through the department of Canadian Heritage by giving grants to art galleries, as well as by establishing and funding art schools and colleges across the country, and through the Canada Council for the Arts.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The Canada Council Art Bank also helps artists by buying and publicizing their work.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Great achievements in art in Canada are recognized through various awards and prizes, such as the Molson Prize, the Audain Prize for the Visual Arts, and the Governor General's Visual and Media Arts Awards.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian music reflects a variety of regional scenes.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada has developed a vast music infrastructure that includes church halls, chamber halls, conservatories, academies, performing arts centres, record companies, radio stations, music charts, and television music video channels.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Government support programs, such as the Canada Music Fund, assist a wide range of musicians and entrepreneurs who create, produce and market original and diverse Canadian music.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] As a result of its cultural importance, as well as government initiatives and regulations, the Canadian music industry is one of the largest in the world, producing internationally renowned composers, musicians, and ensembles.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Achievements in music are recognized through various awards and prizes, most notably, the Juno Awards presented by the Canadian Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The country also hosts numerous music halls of fame with the Canadian Music Hall of Fame honouring musicians at the national level for their lifetime achievements.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] "God Save the King" has been used in Canada since the late 1700s and is the country's de facto royal anthem.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Patriotic music by Canadians dates back over 200 years, with "The Bold Canadian", written in 1812, popular throughout the 19th century.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] "The Maple Leaf Forever", written in 1866, was popular and served as an unofficial national anthem of English Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] "O Canada", originally composed in French in 1880, also served as an unofficial national anthem during the 20th century and was adopted as the country's official anthem in 1980.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada's media is highly autonomous, diverse, and very regionalized.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The *Broadcasting Act* declares "the system should serve to safeguard, enrich, and strengthen the cultural, political, social, and economic fabric of Canada".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada has a well-developed media sector, but its cultural output—particularly in English films, television shows, and magazines—is often overshadowed by imports from the United States.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] As a result, the preservation of a distinctly Canadian culture is supported by federal government programs, laws, and institutions such as the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC), the National Film Board of Canada (NFB), and the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian mass media, both print and digital, and in both official languages, is largely dominated by a "handful of corporations".
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The largest of these corporations is the country's national public broadcaster, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation, which also plays a significant role in producing domestic cultural content, operating its own radio and TV networks in both English and French.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In addition to the CBC, some provincial governments offer their own public educational TV broadcast services as well, such as TVOntario and Télé-Québec.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Non-news media content in Canada, including film and television, is influenced both by local creators as well as by imports from the United States, the United Kingdom, Australia, and France.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In an effort to reduce the amount of foreign-made media, government interventions in television broadcasting can include both regulation of content and public financing.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian tax laws limit foreign competition in magazine advertising.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada's official national sports are ice hockey and lacrosse.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Other major professional games include curling, basketball, baseball, soccer, and football.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Great achievements in Canadian sports are recognized by numerous "Halls of Fame" and museums, such as Canada's Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canada shares several major professional sports leagues with the United States.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadian teams in these leagues include seven franchises in the National Hockey League, three Major League Soccer teams, and one team in each of Major League Baseball and the National Basketball Association.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Other popular professional competitions include the Canadian Football League, National Lacrosse League, the Canadian Premier League, and the curling tournaments hosted by Curling Canada.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Canadians identified hockey as their preferred sport for viewing, followed by soccer and then basketball.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] In terms of participation, swimming was the most commonly reported sport by over one-third (35 percent) of Canadians in 2023.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] This was closely followed by cycling (33 percent) and running (27 percent).
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] Sports such as golf, volleyball, badminton, bowling, and martial arts are also widely enjoyed at the youth and amateur levels.
[src:apple-jacks/canada-p02] The country co-hosted the 2026 FIFA World Cup alongside Mexico and the United States.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The **Caribbean** is a geo-political region in the middle of the Americas centered around the Caribbean Sea in the North Atlantic Ocean, mostly overlapping with the West Indies.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Bordered by North America to the north and also the west through Central America, and South America to the south, it comprises numerous islands, cays, islets, reefs, and banks.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] It also includes the coastal areas on the continental mainland of the Americas bordering the region from the Yucatán Peninsula in North America through Central America to the Guianas in South America.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Situated largely on the Caribbean plate, the region has thousands of islands, islets, reefs, and cays.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Island arcs delineate the northern and eastern edges of the Caribbean Sea: the Greater Antilles in the north and the Lesser Antilles, which includes the Leeward Islands, Windward Islands, and the Leeward Antilles, to the east and south.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The nearby northwestern Lucayan Archipelago, comprising The Bahamas and the Turks and Caicos Islands, and the island of Barbados in the Lesser Antilles, are considered to be a part of the Caribbean despite not bordering the Caribbean Sea.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] All the islands in the Antilles, including the Lucayan Archipelago, form the West Indies, a term often interchangeable with the *Caribbean*.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The archipelago of Bermuda is not part of the Caribbean, as it lies in the Sargasso Sea to the north, but it is an associate member of the Caribbean Community.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] As with the coastal areas of the mainland, Guyana, Suriname, and French Guiana, even if they do not border the Caribbean Sea, are often completely included within the Caribbean due to their strong political and cultural ties with the region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Geopolitically, the islands of the Caribbean are often regarded as a subregion of North America, though sometimes they are included in Middle America, or regarded as its own subregion as the *Caribbean*.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Caribbean is sometimes considered alongside Central America as a region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Generally, the Caribbean region is organized into 33 political entities, including 13 sovereign states, 12 dependencies, 7 overseas territories, and various disputed territories.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] From 15 December 1954 to 10 October 2010, there was a territory known as the Netherlands Antilles composed of five islands, all of which were Dutch dependencies.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] From 3 January 1958 to 31 May 1962, there was also a short-lived political union called the British West Indies Federation composed of ten English-speaking Caribbean territories, all of which were then British dependencies.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The region takes its name from the Caribs, an Amerindian ethnic group historically present in the Lesser Antilles and parts of adjacent South America that the Spanish colonists named the region after at the time of the European conquest of the Americas.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The two most prevalent pronunciations of "Caribbean" outside the Caribbean are /ˌkærɪˈbiːən/ (*KARR-ə-BEE-ən*), with the primary stress on the third syllable, and /kəˈrɪbiən/ (*kə-RIB-ee-ən*), with the stress on the second.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Most authorities of the last century preferred the stress on the third syllable.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] This is the older of the two pronunciations, but the stressed-second-syllable variant has been established for over 75 years.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] It has been suggested that speakers of British English prefer /ˌkærɪˈbiːən/ (*KARR-ə-BEE-ən*) while North American speakers more typically use /kəˈrɪbiən/ (*kə-RIB-ee-ən*), but major American dictionaries and other sources list the stress on the third syllable as more common in American English too.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] According to the American version of Oxford Online Dictionaries, the stress on the second syllable is becoming more common in UK English and is increasingly considered "by some" to be more up to date and more "correct".
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Its principal ones are geographical and political.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Caribbean can also be expanded to include territories with strong cultural and historical connections to Africa, slavery, European colonisation and the plantation system.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The oldest evidence of humans in the Caribbean is in southern Trinidad at Banwari Trace, where remains have been found from 7,000 years ago.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] These pre-ceramic sites, which belong to the Archaic (pre-ceramic) age, have been termed Ortoiroid.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The earliest archaeological evidence of human settlement in Hispaniola dates to about 3600 BC, but the reliability of these finds is questioned.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Consistent dates of 3100 BC appear in Cuba.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The earliest dates in the Lesser Antilles are from 2000 BC in Antigua.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] A lack of pre-ceramic sites in the Windward Islands and differences in technology suggest that these Archaic settlers may have Central American origins.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Whether an Ortoiroid colonization of the islands took place is uncertain, but there is little evidence of one.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] DNA studies changed some of the traditional beliefs about pre-Columbian indigenous history.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] According to *National Geographic*, "studies confirm that a wave of pottery-making farmers—known as Ceramic Age people—set out in canoes from the northeastern coast of South America starting some 2,500 years ago and island-hopped across the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] They were not, however, the first colonizers.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] On many islands they encountered a foraging people who arrived some 6,000 or 7,000 years ago ...
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Between 400 BC and 200 BC, the first ceramic-using agriculturalists, the Saladoid culture, entered Trinidad from South America.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] They expanded up the Orinoco River to Trinidad, and then spread rapidly up the islands of the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Some time after 250 AD another group, the Barancoid, entered Trinidad.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Barancoid society collapsed along the Orinoco around 650 AD and another group, the Arauquinoid, expanded into these areas and up the Caribbean chain.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Around 1300 AD a new group, the Mayoid, entered Trinidad and remained the dominant culture until Spanish settlement.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Taínos are subdivided into Classic Taínos, who occupied Puerto Rico and part of Hispaniola; Western Taínos, who occupied the Bahamian archipelago, Cuba, Jamaica, and part of Hispaniola; and the Eastern Taínos, who occupied the northern Lesser Antilles.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The southern Lesser Antilles, including Martinique and Trinidad, were inhabited by both Carib-speaking and Arawak-speaking groups.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Christopher Columbus arrived in the Caribbean on the island of Hispaniola in 1492.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Soon afterward, both Portuguese and Spanish explorers began claiming territories in Central and South America.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] These early colonies brought gold to Europe; most specifically England, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] These nations hoped to establish profitable colonies in the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Colonial rivalries made the Caribbean a battleground for European wars for centuries.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] In 1512, after pressure from Dominican friars, the Laws of Burgos were introduced by the Spanish Crown to better protect the rights of the New World natives.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Spanish used a form of slavery called the *Encomienda*, where slaves would be awarded to the conquistadors, who were charged with protecting and converting their slaves.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] This had a devastating impact on the population, so starting in 1503, slaves from Africa were imported to the colony.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Jamaica was ceded to England by Spain while both Martinique and the western third of Hispaniola were ceded to France.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] While early slave traders were Portuguese and Spanish, known as the First Atlantic System, by the 17th century the trade became dominated by British, French, and Dutch merchants.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] This was known as the Second Atlantic System.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] 5 million African slaves would be taken to the Caribbean, and around half would be traded to the British Caribbean islands.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Slavery was abolished first in the Dutch Empire in 1814.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Spain abolished slavery in its empire in 1811, with the exceptions of Cuba, Puerto Rico, and Santo Domingo.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Slavery was not abolished in Cuba until 1886.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Britain abolished the slave trade in 1807, and slavery proper in 1833.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] France abolished slavery in its colonies in 1848.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Caribbean was known for pirates, especially between 1640 and 1680.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The term "buccaneer" is often used to describe a pirate operating in this region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Caribbean region was war-torn throughout much of its colonial history, but the wars were often based in Europe, with only minor battles fought in the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Some wars, however, were born of political turmoil in the Caribbean itself.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] In 1791, a slave rebellion in the French colony of Saint-Domingue led to the establishment in 1804 of Haiti, the first republic in the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Neighboring Santo Domingo (present-day Dominican Republic) would attain its independence on three separate occasions in 1821, 1844 and 1865.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Cuba became independent in 1898 following American intervention in the War of Independence during the Spanish-American war.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Following the war, Spain's last colony in the Americas, Puerto Rico, became an unincorporated territory of the United States.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The U.S., since the Monroe Doctrine in the 19th century, has excerted a major influence over the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The so called Banana Wars in the early 20th century saw the temporary U.S. occupations of Haiti and the Dominican Republic.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Between the 1960s and '80s, most of the British holdings in the Caribbean achieved political independence, starting with Jamaica in 1962, then Trinidad and Tobago (1962), Guyana (1966), Barbados (1966), The Bahamas (1973), Grenada (1974), Dominica (1978), St.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Vincent and the Grenadines (1979), Belize (1981) Antigua and Barbuda (1981), and St.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] In case of the Netherlands, the Netherlands Antilles received autonomy status within the Kingdom in 1954, with Aruba receiving its own in 1986 and Curaçao and St.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Presently, the United States, Britain, France and the Netherlands still have some Caribbean possessions.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] During the Cold War, the U.S. would again intervene militarily into Caribbean countries including Cuba, the Dominican Republic and Grenada.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The decline of the export industries meant a need to diversify the economies of the Caribbean territories.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The tourism industry started developing in the early 20th century, rapidly developing in the 1960s when regular international flights made vacations affordable and is now a $50 billion industry.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The geography and climate in the Caribbean region varies: Some islands in the region have relatively flat terrain of non-volcanic origin.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] These islands include Aruba (which has minor volcanic features), Curaçao, Barbados, Bonaire, the Cayman Islands, Saint Croix, The Bahamas, and Antigua.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Others possess rugged towering mountain-ranges like the islands of Saint Martin, Cuba, Hispaniola, Puerto Rico, Jamaica, Dominica, Montserrat, Saba, Sint Eustatius, Saint Kitts, Saint Lucia, Saint Thomas, Saint John, Tortola, Grenada, Saint Vincent, Guadeloupe, Martinique and Trinidad and Tobago.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Definitions of the terms Greater Antilles and Lesser Antilles often vary.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] As part of the Puerto Rico Bank and the Puerto Rico-Virgin Islands microplate, the Virgin Islands are sometimes included with the Greater Antilles.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The term Lesser Antilles is often used to define an island arc that includes Grenada but excludes Trinidad and Tobago and the Leeward Antilles.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The waters of the Caribbean Sea host large, migratory schools of fish, turtles, and coral reef formations.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Puerto Rico Trench, located on the fringe of the Atlantic Ocean and Caribbean Sea just to the north of the island of Puerto Rico, is the deepest point in all of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The region sits in the line of several major shipping routes with the Panama Canal connecting the western Caribbean Sea with the Pacific Ocean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The climate of the area is tropical, varying from tropical rainforest in some areas to tropical monsoon and tropical savanna in others.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] There are also some locations that are arid climates with considerable drought in some years, and the peaks of mountains tend to have cooler temperate climates.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Rainfall varies with elevation, size and water currents, such as the cool upwellings that keep the ABC islands arid.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Warm, moist trade winds blow consistently from the east, creating both rain forest and semi arid climates across the region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The tropical rainforest climates include lowland areas near the Caribbean Sea from Costa Rica north to Belize, as well as the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico, while the more seasonal dry tropical savanna climates are found in Cuba, northern Colombia and Venezuela, and southern Yucatán, Mexico.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Arid climates are found along the extreme northern coast of Venezuela out to the islands including Aruba and Curaçao, as well as the northwestern tip of Yucatán.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] While the region generally is sunny much of the year, the wet season from May through November sees more frequent cloud cover (both broken and overcast), while the dry season from December through April is more often clear to mostly sunny.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Seasonal rainfall is divided into 'dry' and 'wet' seasons, with the latter six months of the year being wetter than the first half.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The air temperature is hot much of the year, varying from 25 to 33 C (77 F to 90 F) between the wet and dry seasons.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Seasonally, monthly mean temperatures vary from about 5 C (7 F) in the northern most regions, to less than 3 C in the southernmost areas of the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Hurricane season is from June to November, but they occur more frequently in August and September and more common in the northern islands of the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Hurricanes that sometimes batter the region usually strike northward of Grenada and to the west of Barbados.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The principal hurricane belt arcs to northwest of the island of Barbados in the Eastern Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] A great example being recent events of Hurricane Irma devastating the island of Saint Martin during the 2017 hurricane season.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Sea surface temperatures change little annually, normally running from 30 °C (87 °F) in the warmest months to 26 °C (76 °F) in the coolest months.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The air temperature is warm year round, in the 70s, 80s and 90s, and varies from winter to summer about 2–5 degrees on the southern islands and about a 10–20 degrees difference on the northern islands of the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The northern islands, like The Bahamas, Cuba, Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic, may be influenced by continental masses during winter months, such as cold fronts.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The British West Indies were united by the United Kingdom into a West Indies Federation between 1958 and 1962.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The independent countries formerly part of the B.W.I. still have a joint cricket team that competes in Test matches, One Day Internationals and Twenty20 Internationals.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The West Indian cricket team includes the South American nation of Guyana, the only former British colony on the mainland of that continent.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] In addition, these countries share the University of the West Indies as a regional entity.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The university consists of three main campuses in Jamaica, Barbados and Trinidad and Tobago, a smaller campus in The Bahamas and Resident Tutors in other contributing territories such as Trinidad.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Caribbean islands have one of the world's most diverse ecosystems.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The animals, fungi, and plants are Conservation International biodiversity hotspots because of their exceptionally diverse terrestrial and marine ecosystems, ranging from montane cloud forests to tropical rainforest to cactus scrublands.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The region also contains about 8% (by surface area) of the world's coral reefs along with extensive seagrass meadows, often found in the shallow marine waters bordering the region's island and continental coasts.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] For the fungi, there is a checklist based on nearly 90,000 records derived from specimens in reference collections, published accounts, and field observations.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] It includes more than 11,250 species of fungi recorded in the region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The checklist is not exhaustive, and it is likely that the true number of fungal species already known in the Caribbean is higher.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The number of fungal species in the Caribbean, including species not yet recorded, is likely far higher, given the generally accepted estimate that only about 7% of all fungi worldwide have been discovered.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Estimates have been made for endemic fungal species on some Caribbean islands.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] For Cuba, 2,200 species of fungi have been tentatively identified as possible endemics of the island; for Puerto Rico, the number is 789; for the Dominican Republic, 699; for Trinidad and Tobago, 407.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Many ecosystems in the Caribbean islands have been affected by deforestation, pollution, and human encroachment.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The arrival of the first humans is correlated with extinction of giant owls and dwarf ground sloths.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The hotspot contains dozens of highly threatened animals (birds, mammals, and reptiles), fungi, and plants.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The threatened animals include the Puerto Rican amazon, two species of solenodon (giant shrews) in Cuba and Hispaniola, and the Cuban crocodile.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The region's coral reefs, which contain about 70 species of hard corals and 500 to 700 species of reef-associated fishes, have undergone rapid decline in ecosystem integrity and are considered vulnerable to global warming and ocean acidification.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] According to a UNEP report, the Caribbean coral reefs might go extinct in next 20 years due to human population explosion along the coastlines, overfishing, pollution of coastal areas, and global warming.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Some Caribbean islands have terrain that Europeans found suitable for cultivation for agriculture.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Tobacco was an important early crop during the colonial era, but was eventually overtaken by sugarcane production as the region's staple crop.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Sugar was produced from sugarcane for export to Europe.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Cuba and Barbados were historically the largest producers of sugar.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The tropical plantation system came to dominate Caribbean settlement.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Other islands were found to have terrain unsuited for agriculture, for example Dominica, which remains heavily forested.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The islands in the southern Lesser Antilles, Aruba, Bonaire and Curaçao, are extremely arid, making them unsuitable for agriculture, but they have salt pans that were exploited by the Dutch.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Sea water was pumped into shallow ponds, producing coarse salt when the water evaporated.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The natural environmental diversity of the Caribbean islands has led to recent growth in eco-tourism.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] This type of tourism is growing on islands lacking sandy beaches and dense human populations.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Caribbean societies are very different from other Western societies in terms of size, culture, and degree of mobility of their citizens.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The current economic and political problems the states face individually are common to all Caribbean states.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Regional development has contributed to attempts to subdue current problems and avoid projected problems.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] From a political and economic perspective, regionalism serves to make Caribbean states active participants in current international affairs through collective coalitions.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] In 1973, the first political regionalism in the Caribbean Basin was created by advances of the English-speaking Caribbean nations through the institution known as the Caribbean Common Market and Community (CARICOM), in Guyana.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Certain scholars have argued both for and against generalizing the political structures of the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] On the one hand the Caribbean states are politically diverse, ranging from socialist systems toward more capitalist Westminster-style parliamentary systems.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Other scholars argue that these differences are superficial, and that they tend to undermine commonalities in the various Caribbean states.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Contemporary Caribbean systems seem to reflect a "blending of traditional and modern patterns, yielding hybrid systems that exhibit significant structural variations and divergent constitutional traditions yet ultimately appear to function in similar ways".
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The political systems of the Caribbean states share similar practices.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The influence of regionalism in the Caribbean is often marginalized.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Some scholars believe that regionalism cannot exist in the Caribbean because each small state is unique.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] On the other hand, scholars also suggest that there are commonalities amongst the Caribbean nations that suggest regionalism exists.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] "Proximity as well as historical ties among the Caribbean nations has led to cooperation as well as a desire for collective action".
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] These attempts at regionalization reflect the nations' desires to compete in the international economic system.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Furthermore, a lack of interest from other major states promoted regionalism in the region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] In recent years, the Caribbean has suffered from a lack of U.S. interest.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] "With the end of the Cold War, U.S. security and economic interests have been focused on other areas.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] As a result there has been a significant reduction in U.S. aid and investment to the Caribbean." The lack of international support for these small, relatively poor states, helped regionalism prosper.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Following the Cold War another issue of importance in the Caribbean has been the reduced economic growth of some Caribbean States due to the United States and European Union's allegations of special treatment toward the region by each other.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The Lomé Convention, which allowed banana exports from the former colonies of the Group of African, Caribbean and Pacific states (ACP) to enter Europe cheaply, came into effect in 1976.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] During the US/EU dispute, the United States threatened to impose large tariffs on European Union goods (up to 100%) to pressure Europe to change the agreement with the Caribbean nations in favour of the Cotonou Agreement.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Farmers in the Caribbean have complained of falling profits and rising costs as the Lomé Convention weakens.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Some farmers have faced increased pressure to turn toward the cultivation of illegal drugs, which has a higher profit margin and fills the sizable demand for these illegal drugs in North America and Europe.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Many Caribbean nations have sought to deepen ties with the continent of Africa.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The African Union-bloc has referred to the Caribbean as the potential "Sixth Region" of the African Union.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Some Caribbean states have already moved to join Africa institutions including Barbados, Grenada, Guyana, and The Bahamas, which have all become members of the African Export Import Bank.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The first inter-regional Africa-Caribbean Community (CARICOM) Summit took place in September 2021.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Caribbean nations have also started to more closely cooperate in the Caribbean Financial Action Task Force and other instruments to add oversight of the offshore industry.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] One of the most important associations that deal with regionalism amongst the nations of the Caribbean Basin has been the Association of Caribbean States (ACS).
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Proposed by CARICOM in 1992, the ACS soon won the support of the other countries of the region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The ACS maintains regionalism within the Caribbean on issues unique to the Caribbean Basin.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] Through coalition building, like the ACS and CARICOM, regionalism has become an undeniable part of the politics and economics of the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The successes of region-building initiatives are still debated by scholars, yet regionalism remains prevalent throughout the Caribbean.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p01] The President of Venezuela, Hugo Chavez launched an economic group called the Bolivarian Alliance for the Americas (ALBA), which several eastern Caribbean islands joined.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The population of the Caribbean is estimated to have been about 750,000 before European contact.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Immigrants from Britain, Italy, France, Spain, the Netherlands, Portugal, and Denmark also arrived, although the mortality rate was high for both groups.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The population is estimated to have reached 2.2 million by 1800.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Immigrants from India, China, Indonesia, and other countries arrived in the mid-19th century as indentured servants.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] After the Atlantic slave trade ended, the population increased naturally.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The regional population was estimated at 37.5 million by 2000.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] On the Cayman Islands, Aruba and Belize mixed-race people form the majority of the population.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] There are also populations of European ancestry; English, French, Dutch, Italian, Portuguese and Spanish ancestry.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Asians, especially those of Chinese, Indian descent, and Javanese Indonesians, form a significant minority in parts of the region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Indians form a plurality of the population in Trinidad and Tobago, Guyana, and Suriname.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Most of their ancestors arrived in the 19th century as indentured laborers.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The Spanish-speaking Caribbean populations are primarily of European, African, or racially mixed origins.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Cuba has a European majority, along with a significant population of African ancestry.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Puerto Rico has a mixed race majority with a mixture of European-African-Native American (tri-racial), and a large White and West African (black) minority.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The Dominican Republic has the largest mixed-race population, primarily descended from Europeans, West Africans, and Amerindians.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The majority of Jamaica is of West African origin, in addition to a significant population of mixed racial background and minorities of Chinese, Europeans, Indians, Indigenous, Jews, and Arabs.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] This is a result of years of importation of slaves and indentured laborers, and migration.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Most multi-racial Jamaicans call themselves either mixed-race or brown.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Similar populations can be found in the Caricom states of Belize, Guyana, Suriname and Trinidad and Tobago.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Trinidad and Tobago has a multiracial cosmopolitan society due to the arrivals of Africans, Indians, Chinese, Arabs and Europeans along with the native indigenous Amerindians population.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] This multiracial mix has created sub-ethnicities that often straddle the boundaries of major ethnicities, such as the Mulatto-Creole, Mestizo, Pardo, Zambo, Dougla, Chindian, Afro-Asians, Eurasian, and Cocoa panyols.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Spanish (64%), French (25%), English (14%), Dutch, Haitian Creole, and Papiamento are the predominant official languages of various countries in the region.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Almost every Caribbean country has a distinct creole language or dialect that serves as its vernacular language.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Most of these do not have official status, with the aforementioned Haitian Creole and Papiamento as notable exceptions.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Other languages such as Caribbean Hindustani, Chinese, Javanese, Arabic, Hmong, Amerindian languages, other African languages, other European languages, and other Indian languages like Telugu are also spoken.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Christianity is the predominant religion in the Caribbean (84.7%).
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Other religions in the region are Hinduism, Islam, Judaism, Rastafari, Buddhism, Chinese folk religion (incl.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Taoism and Confucianism), Baháʼí, Jainism, Sikhism, Kebatinan, Traditional African religions, Yoruba (incl.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Trinidad Orisha), Afro-American religions, (incl.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Santería, Palo, Umbanda, Brujería, Hoodoo, Candomblé, Quimbanda, Orisha, Xangô de Recife, Xangô do Nordeste, Comfa, Espiritismo, Santo Daime, Obeah, Abakuá, Kumina, Winti, Sanse, Cuban Vodú, Dominican Vudú, Louisiana Voodoo, Haitian Vodou, and Vodun).
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Cricket is a very popular sport in the countries and dependencies that formed the British West Indies.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The West Indies cricket team competes in Test matches, One Day Internationals and Twenty20 Internationals.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The West Indies' major domestic competitions are the Regional Four Day Competition (first-class) and the Regional Super50 (List A one-day) and more recently the Caribbean Premier League (Twenty20).
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The regional football governing body is the Caribbean Football Union.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] National teams have competed in the CFU Championship from 1978 to 1988 and the Caribbean Cup since 1989.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The top 4 teams in the tournament qualify for the CONCACAF Gold Cup.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Cuba qualified to the FIFA World Cup in 1938, Haiti in 1974, Jamaica in 1998 and Trinidad and Tobago in 2006.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The CFU Club Championship is the regional tournament for football clubs.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The winner qualified for the CONCACAF Champions' Cup from 1997 until 2008.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Since 2008–09, the top 3 clubs qualify for a preliminary round of the CONCACAF Champions League.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] However, the most popular sport in Cuba, Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, Aruba and Curaçao is baseball.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The Caribbean Series, held since 1949, features the national champions from the top Caribbean leagues.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] The Cuba national team has claimed the Baseball World Cup 25 times, whereas the Dominican Republic won the 2013 World Baseball Classic.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] In the Pan American Games, Cuba has won 12 editions and Dominican Republic once, whereas Puerto Rico earned the silver medal twice.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] In the Central American and Caribbean Games, Cuba has won 15 gold medals, whereas Dominican Republic has won three and Puerto Rico two.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Several Caribbean players have joined the Major League Baseball: in the 2014 there were 82 Dominicans, 19 Cubans and 11 Puerto Ricans.
[src:apple-jacks/caribbean-p02] Notable Caribbean players are Juan Marichal, Pedro Martínez, Roberto Clemente, Orlando Cepeda and Roberto Alomar.
